NEWS

* The resource API only needs a single Event() function now, and it takes a ctx.

* There's a new "watchdog" facility to catch buggy/broken resource on shutdown.

* The precise CheckApply start time was improved. This fixes some rare bugs.

* A fix in the svc resource due to an upstream bug was worked around.

* The file resource can now set the selinux security context

* A new deploy.file_exists function was added.

* etcd/fs uses a ctx instead of a hardcoded timeout. Useful for slow networks.

* The resouce engine correctly starts unpaused and empty fixing more bugs.

* The function engine doesn't send duplicate tables, which speeds up perf a lot.

* The send/recv mechanism was running at the wrong time. This could cause a nil
message in the logs. Now fixed in: e381043f8b10e4b7f509fc9c6b9fd0a2e47bc1bc with
a few more future commits, send/recv is believed to be completely stable.

* All mcl code should be formatted in a standard way to get ready for mclfmt.

* The "lib" context cancellation sequencing was improved.

* There's a new "background" API that resources can use.

* The scheduler was overhauled and we can now to fancy "withdraw" operations.

* The scheduler and the virt resource both now benefit from the background API.

* There's even a "pool" helper for fancier resources like libvirt.

* The autoedge, autogroup and reverse stages support ctx cancellation.

* Fix the operator precedence rules. "Bad code" cases should be caught now.

* LLM's found and fixed a bug that was driving us crazy. Read the commit in:
2266c3c8e9f0cce1960f54a4ce23c516c847b074

* LLM's were able to finish up / write the iter.reduce, iter.zip and
iter.flatten functions. Wow. See: 49e98ddae3ac3cf2bcf1307c3d5f7cd92ae14396

* Fixed an annoying rebuild issue with `make`. No more latent misses.

* Added embedded pprof server. Much easier to do performance measuring.

* Improved performance of the pgraph library and did other cleanups.

* We cache a lot of the work during function graph execution. More can be done!

* Function graph ref counting is much faster and cleaner.

* Performance of the pgraph reachability algorithm was improved dramatically.

* The graphcmp went from O(n^2) to O(n) by using a map based lookup.

* The graphsync operation was sped up significantly.

* Many allocations were reduced all over the code base. More to come!

* Topological sort performance was improved quite a lot. We use it everywhere!

* The etcd/fs "posix" API had about a dozen bugs fixed in it with added tests.

* The deploy package grew a new directory() function.

* Performance of ResGraphMapper improved significantly.

* The govet test and gofmt operation improved quite a lot. Better dev workflow.

* A sneaky packagekit bug was squashed. 28d81c6a06c30f263182f66e0a9dac91ae50d5c5

* The pkg resource and packagekit lib got a lot of improvements.

* We return better error messages for pkg when using unfriendly distros.

* We worked around a long-standing tftp shutdown bug.

* The golang.template function allows a lot more cases. All fields must be title
cased now. Update your templates. Mgmt shuts down safely if you forgot one.

* Invalid templates are caught at startup instead of at runtime!

* The exec resource no longer requires root if we requested running as ourself.

* Deploy supports running over SSH without needing tunnelling.

* The converger now supports notifications on unconverged and is not buggy.

* We added a new "exit" resource. Useful for building applications.

* The user resource got a major refactor and supports mock testing. It's tricky!

* The user resource also watches the /etc/group list. We fixed a lot of bugs.

* The group resource got some fixes as well.

* The tftp and dhcp servers don't run until their "CheckApply" turns them "on".

* We have added an mgmt "check" subcommand to make static testing easier.

* The print resource is now more correct and has state. Who'd have figured!

* The engine grew a new timeout meta param. Use it instead of per-resource code.

* The fmt.printf command now supports a %T verb.

* The Meta:poll metaparam allows negative values to ask for "one shot" events.
It's unclear if we'll keep this behaviour long-term so don't rely on it without
telling us about your use-case please.

* Added an http:client resource that also supports long polling with the
http:server file resources.

* There's a companion net/http.resource function. It's a beautiful demonstration
of the functions+resources model that I've been working on for so long. Finally
proud to merge a really useful example of this.

* The gzip and tar resource support cancellation.

* Added golangci-lint tests in. Fixed many nitpicks. Added a bunch of sub lints.

* Fixed some possible issues with the net resource.

* Fixed some small bugs in the mount resource. More work is needed here.

* Fixed some rare SSH connection deploy issues. I think we're block free now.

* Fixed a small spin in our local API.

* The pgraph library now stores the reverse adjacency maps for performance.

* Made a bunch of method additions/changes in pgraph for increased performance.

* The GraphSync performance is now measured and improved significantly. A 10,000
node graph goes from ~1000ms to 16ms. Wow

* A tree of 10,000 autoedge nodes goes from 17,109ms to 53ms. Wow

* The autoedge algorithm got a major overhaul to support such improvements.

* Fixed a rare race in the weird os.system function. (Don't use it anyways!)

* A backlog of misc tests and bugs were fixed or ruled out.

* Some overflow related issues were found and fixed.

* The gosec linter was run and all issues were fixed or tagged. It's tested now.

* We added spell checking as a test case. Might as well keep things neat!

* 1,000 node graphs went from autogrouping in seconds or hours to subsecond in
most cases. A long chain of 1,000 went from 162107ms -> 179ms. Wow!

* The autogrouping algorithm got a major overhaul to support such improvements.

* Clarify that the filteredgraph API is fixed and race-safe now.

* We're looking for support to write Amazon, Cloudflare, DigitalOcean, Google,
Hetzner, OVH, etc, resources if anyone is interested, reach out to us.
Particularly if there is support from those organizations as well.

* Many other bug fixes, changes, etc...

* See the git log for more NEWS, and for anything notable I left out!


NLNET

The nlnet grant requires that you specify specific tasks as "goals" to achieve,
and when those tasks are completed, you write up those details and they make a
donation. What follows is that report, since it provides more detail that what
you would usually see in release notes, and there's no reason it should be
private.

## Task #2: Parser refresh with trailing line, newline, and other fixups

This patch was a giant relief to finally land. In my inexpertise when I first
added the language, I didn't differentiate between single line lists, maps,
structs, and multi-line ones. As a result, as silly as it sounds, trailing
commas were *required* when using any of these expressions. For example you'd
have to write:

$some_list = [1, 2, 3,]

instead of:

$some_list = [1, 2, 3]

It may only be a small comma, but it was a lot of work, and it really adds some
professional polish to our project. The same comma logic is applied to all of
the expressions in the project.

The main work was done in:

> lang: Use trailing commas on multiline declarations only
> c7acc753d76f747376928ebb91925e5f1aa3cb27

A contributor then noticed two additional edge cases which we polished in:

> lang: parser: Error on invalid commas
> ce8791201e3faa360d579d6da6b69f7cb4eb7fb4

> lang: parser: Reject invalid types
> e65f1de0afe32e84909257d3f1756dbe999ed7fa

Lastly, this work was an important pre-requisite to eventually being about to
add automatic mcl code formatting, which we hope to tackle in the future!


## Task #3: Scheduler rewrite and improvements

Our original scheduler was built as a proof-of-concept, but it was never used in
very serious production workloads and as a result it had some major flaws. In
particular it lacked the ability to programmatically "withdraw" scheduled hosts
which is crucial for fancier dynamic scheduling.


### Task #3a: The work starts with:

> engine, lib: Add background plumbing
> 446f8928fcd788b2c02102bfb6883d83a3c0dc56

where we implemented a generic "background worker" interface that resources can
use. This is actually quite significant because it lets us have all sorts of
resources share a common "worker" which must be a singleton. The resources don't
have to worry about handling the graph analysis, this is all automatic!


### Task #3b: Next the actual scheduler modernization itself.

> engine, etcd, scheduler: Add a modern scheduler
> 446f8928fcd788b2c02102bfb6883d83a3c0dc56

(Note that this work took weeks, the git timestamps were refreshed before commit
when fixing misc test failures that we missed before our final CI run.)

Getting the precise behaviour to align with the etcd API was very challenging,
particularly since it's not well-documented. This patch required a lot of deep
reading of the upstream source. This patch fully implements the "withdraw"
capability which lets us build distributed systems where a group of peers first
put their "names" into the proverbial hat when they believe a given task is
necessary, next the cluster elects some number of them (so that they don't all
run simultaneously) and finally when they each complete their individual task,
they "withdraw" themselves so that a subsequent member can be scheduled. More
than one can run simultaneously too!

This patch updated both the internal API's and interfaces, as well as the mcl
API used for the function and the resource. We believe these are more "correct"
now. They are also better abstracted which could allow a third-party to add a
more powerful external scheduler if they had very large enterprise scheduling
needs.

Lastly this also makes it possible to add weighted or node-specific data to the
scheduling decisions if we want to really make things fancier!


### Task #3c: Finally with this work out of the way, we got to:

> engine: resources: Port virt resource to background API
> 63e45480c07514edb10ad1bdb595b7791b834474

> engine: Add a background pool helper
> acf739446d718117b6a7c01029d0559ee6747e09

> engine: resources: Port the virt background api to a pool
> 1af498a655036e616385886faba02a58bda00cf0

These three commits ported our important libvirt to this new API and also solved
a long-standing deadlock/race which we would experience when using the virt
resource.

This issue was so significant, we even added custom "watchdog" detection to more
easily detect the situation. (If you're curious we did that in:
"engine: graph, util: Add a watchdog facility for resource shutdown" -
45f30bab585df66587287a59fa266d03278c2726) We're glad to report that after the
aforementioned fixes, we no longer experience these issues, and we also have
better code!

As an addendum, included in this set were related bug fixes, improvements, etc:

> etcd: scheduler: Add missing namespace value
> d5dd2b4801795d5691eb179582f8825123a1cd75

> etcd: util: Add an election package
> cda8d62b16fe8642941d77b93ec27d20e71d380c

> etcd: scheduler: Use the new election package
> 517016a6e67d799798ed42b1421f88170b5af1ec

> etcd: scheduler: Don't prematurely orphan during graph swap
> 0d36a243221995a70e295de83704130f9195ccce


## Task #6: Converger rewrite

We struggled to implement this at a recent hackathon but failed. It's a very
important feature needed for this new generation of "real-time" tooling, and as
a result, nobody else seems to have had to ever implement something like this,
and we had to get it right ourselves. I believe we succeeded:

> converger: Rewrite the converger to support dual state
> 12849874bff8934b7f116877c668ed17c8528c05

The code is highly concurrent, and I will say that the race detector helped me
out significantly. I was actually almost ready to merge this when on the final
CI run it caught an unusual (but legitimate) race! If you're curious what the
sneaky race was, it's documented here:

https://github.com/purpleidea/mgmt/blob/12849874bff8934b7f116877c668ed17c8528c05/converger/converger.go#L257

Try and wrap your head around that one!

In particular, for those wishing to experiment at home, we now see "converged"
and "unconverged" messages. Demo:

$ echo true > /tmp/flipflop
$ mgmt run --tmp-prefix --converger-timeout 5 lang examples/lang/background0.mcl
[snip]
01:25:05 engine: background(test): running...
01:25:06 engine: background(test): running...
01:25:07 engine: background(test): running...
01:25:08 engine: background(test): running...
01:25:09 main: converger: converged for 5 seconds

[snip]

$ echo false > /tmp/flipflop

[continued...]

01:25:11 gapi: lang: interpret: interpreting...
01:25:11 gapi: generating new graph...
01:25:11 main: new graph took: 217ns
01:25:11 engine: autoedge: building...
01:25:11 main: auto edges took: 14.098µs
01:25:11 engine: autogroup: algorithm: wrappedGrouper: NonReachabilityGrouper...
01:25:11 main: auto grouping took: 28.576µs
01:25:11 main: resource topological sort took: 1.014µs
01:25:11 main: send/recv building took: 3.73µs
01:25:11 main: commit...
01:25:11 engine: graph sync...
01:25:11 engine: background(test): stopped!
01:25:11 main: export cleanup took: 14.556µs
01:25:11 main: converger: unconverged...
01:25:11 main: graph: Vertices(0), Edges(0)
01:25:11 main: waiting...
01:25:16 main: converger: converged for 5 seconds

As silly as this sounds, it's incredibly important for sysadmins to know if
there is working that is still ongoing, or if they're waiting on network or
something that is blocked.


## Task 4/5: Graph related, dependencies for both tasks

Made edge deleting O(1), something we previously never did before.

> pgraph: Add DeleteEdgeBetween method
> 1f33b481e2c047ef1000057225d70a2f45b9fb58

Previously, we would directly modify the internal adjacency map for direct
performance. We needed to move beyond that, so we could eventually support a
reverse adjacency map. So here's a cleanup:

> pgraph: Use the graph API instead of raw map writes in GraphSync
> 9a36537ff76e6d7677de46e060680a741ffdd29b

Similarly, we can improve the efficiency of going through adjacency by using
more precise API calls:

> engine: graph: autogroup: Use the pgraph API in VertexMerge
> 842f0a6b58bc96c862f0193eb444b0c93360db23

The big change for the pgraph library now happens that consumes a bit more
memory, but makes many operations significantly faster:

> pgraph: Add a reverse adjacency index
> ce9d2c514ee1d92cba6c10e987ed107dd965b0b3

Here we make use of those new efficiencies:

> pgraph: Use the reverse index for incoming edge lookups
> 5935dbd17af755197cbe36cab9101c861272496d

In this commit, we have a bonus fixup moving our DFS algo to using a lookup map.

> pgraph: Use a visited map in DFS and DisconnectedGraphs
> bb7e9fce30b709e95fb956d3a25e62cc40a91147

And trivial fixes like:

pgraph: Optimize simple vertex lookup function
> d114df34d7520c1087f84ef3551dd32a997cf550

Allocation optimization came to light with a fix in:

> pgraph: Start the HasPath traversal structures small
> 708cef93f0765e90e0becfb6a7fa6602c14d1f5c

As well as lazy graph allocation in:

> pgraph: Allocate the inner adjacency maps lazily
> 9f90a5664ab540acbf7ad13e35cfed45aa535eba

## Task #5: Autoedge improvements

We start with some benchmarking to measure whether our work really helped.

> engine: resources: Add an autoedge benchmark
> 3d2b31d1daafa66a72486726f2f1783bc954df64

The bulk of the algorithmic work consists of two major parts. The first involves
being smart about caching and lookups. We also make sure to never run a function
twice. The lookup trick involves using the reflect.Type as the key. Our earlier
purely human work looked at this approach, and we were finally able to
substantiate it with this commit.

A second optimization is that we can have a single unique "hash" for a node edge
to build a relationship between two vertices. For example, a file resource might
use the "path" as the hash.

> engine: graph: autoedge: Major autoedge restructuring
> 1da5135a4d46d7eaf22d24aef9035554b5b84bca

Finally we implement the hashing API where the bulk of our performance is lost.

> engine: resources: file: Implement UIDHash for FileUID
> 43d56e9a48c98fe6b30f89fba3d8c4e847202853

Lastly we plumb through our ctx to modernize this algorithm.

> engine: Pass ctx into autoedge call
> 8976ce58bc38b3f9d59b2ed20e6500e7326f1500

And do a small cleanup for consistency:

> engine: graph: autoedge: Don't be too verbose
> eee5dcde57b34a66f660f48a93e8fb9278161242

The total autoedge performance improvements were significant. In our benchmarks
you can see:

BenchmarkAutoEdge/tree/100      1.6ms -> 0.41ms
BenchmarkAutoEdge/tree/1000     133ms -> 4.7ms
BenchmarkAutoEdge/tree/10000    17109ms -> 53ms
BenchmarkAutoEdge/flat/1000     710ms -> 3.1ms

Longer benchmarks that show allocations and deltas and more are also available
in the source.

## Task #4: Autogroup improvements

We again start off with some benchmarking:

> engine: graph: autogroup: Add benchmarks
> 30392851d2b6b465e720990c8386cefffb2a5c67

> engine: graph: autogroup: Add more performance tests
> cbd0a0d1c783574cdebe82121aba2471f7e983d3

Instead of running the topological sort every merge, we do it once per run:

> engine: graph: autogroup: Validate acyclicity once per run, not per merge
> 33236f9f3bff3e56572d408169b413eeb04e0984

We also move to an "unsafe" reachability algorithm which doesn't check for
cycles, since that check is expensive. We work out that it's provably not needed
especially since we check at the end.

> engine: graph: autogroup: Use ReachabilityUnsafe in VertexMerge
> d4e9cb9a13fee8dc8c2acda2c11ddd11fefc83ae

The O(n^2) traversal on each vertex merge can get replace with two operations:

> engine: graph: autogroup: Replace the VertexMerge edge scan with lookups
> 613f4056d5392645a23c8800bd8f20c8f32ed40b

And an early "Vertex Viable" check removes the need for most uses of the compare
(Cmp) which is much more expensive.

> engine: Add VertexViable to the AutoGrouper interface
> 1723dad7e661c792dc1725a22f0a98c15d34a301

Since our resources have names such as "pkg", "file" and "http:server:file" we
can benefit from this pattern and use it as an index to know which resources can
autogroup! They must share a common prefix to be able to match!

engine: graph: autogroup: Skip pairs with differing first kind chunks
> b1ac60645276367bea27c6d22e3789665f5c0cae

In order to save the `String()` name computation, we do it only on merge success
which reduces allocations and increases performance.

> engine: graph: autogroup: Only stringify pairs which try to merge
> e144dd55ffb06ac337b35b29a7ec3d28bb8f8a94

And once we've done a merge, we don't use it any more in the iterator.

> engine: graph: autogroup: Skip merged away vertices in the iterator
> 4913689ad0fe31e20c0263ecd3fa7bcae19123bb

Lastly, the biggest change so far: we actually merge the new grouper algorithm.
This caches the expensive reachability lookups and makes use of all the earlier
optimizations, such as the "VertexViable" function. The simpler lookups are now
much faster!

> engine: graph: autogroup: Add cached non reachability grouper
> 136b647e6084e2bf58c5b28a075024ab84f1ea17

Here we actually enable that new algorithm.

> engine, lang, lib: Switch to the new autogrouper
> edcd85669a669b2748e6f52b53b5ba84baa7291a

The total autogroup performance improvements were significant. In our benchmarks
you can see:

BenchmarkAutoGroup/group/100      4.4ms -> 2.1ms
BenchmarkAutoGroup/group/1000     1534ms -> 1310ms
BenchmarkAutoGroup/letters/100    23ms -> 2.3ms
BenchmarkAutoGroup/letters/1000   1609ms -> 41ms
BenchmarkAutoGroup/chain/100      650ms -> 3.6ms
BenchmarkAutoGroup/chain/1000     (untested, hours) -> 460ms
BenchmarkAutoGroup/disabled/1000  162107ms -> 179ms

Longer benchmarks that show allocations and deltas and more are also available
in the source.

We're incredibly thankful to nlnet for sponsoring all this work, and look we
look forward to working more with them in the future.


BUGS/TODO

* Function values getting _passed_ to resources doesn't work yet, but it's not a
blocker, but it would definitely be useful. We're looking into it.

* We don't have any aarch64 hardware, so no more arm64 builds or testing until
we get a donation or sponsor for that unfortunately.

* We don't have the <|> operator merged yet. Expect that when we do this, we'll
consider removing the || (default) operator. This is the only pending language
change that I know of, and these cases are easily caught by the compiler and can
be easily patched.


